content.thinking:
I see that the mockData.ts file is using the old BaziData type where `dayMaster` is a string. The new BaziData type has `dayMaster` as an object with `element`, `character`, and `description` properties. I need to update the mockData to use the new format, but also keep backward compatibility. Let me check if the BaziData type has legacy support.Looking at BaziSummaryCard.tsx, I can see that the type does have legacy support:

```typescript
export interface BaziData {
  dayMaster?: {
    element: string;
    character: string;
    description: string;
  };
  fiveElements?: Record<string, number>;
  dailyFortune?: string;
  // Legacy support
  pattern?: string;
  fortuneLevel?: 1 | 2 | 3 | 4 | 5;
  todayFortune?: string;
}
```

But the mockData uses `dayMaster: "ç”²æœ¨"` which is a string, not an object. I need to update the mockData to use the correct format.

Also, looking at ZodiacData type:
```typescript
export interface ZodiacData {
  sun?: { sign: string; keywords: string[] };
  moon?: { sign: string; keywords: string[] };
  rising?: { sign: string; keywords: string[] };
  transitHighlight?: string;
  // Legacy support
  sunSign?: string;
  ascendant?: string;
  todayEnergy?: string;
  energyLevel?: 1 | 2 | 3 | 4 | 5;
}
```

The mockData uses the legacy format with `sunSign`, `ascendant`, etc. which is fine since we have legacy support.

The issue is that the type definition expects `dayMaster` to be an object, but the mockData is setting it to a string. 

Now I need to fix the mockData by converting the `dayMaster` string value into the proper object structure with element, character, and description fields.

